segments.text: Actually, it has gotten some very interesting reviews.
There was a book published.
I was trying to think.
It was Lexington or Heath.
I can't remember publishers that had a chapter in it dealing with MOPAC and citizen conflicts with local governments.
And I'm not sure he did a real good job.
But I have a friend who will go nameless that's with the highway department.
And...
And I will go so far as to say that they have done a major analysis of Mopac and land use impacts and change and traced it historically.
And they cannot find where Mopac, per se, has had any substantial impact on the surrounding neighborhoods.
Now, there are two reasons for this, and they were design factors built into the freeway.
One is there's no access road.
And so not only is there no access road, but

Interestingly enough, my friend who did this study, which has not been released and may never see the light of day, found that the expressway itself did not make any substantial impacts in terms of land use patterns or changes.
that, in fact, it tended to verify what was already happening.
There was already a conversion process going on in the area.
Conversion from what to what?
Well, basically from single family houses to some corner stores, markets, to small apartments, six, eight unit townhouse apartments.
And part of this reflects the fact that Mopac extends past, essentially, the west fringe of the University of Texas, which
logically was an area for redevelopment at higher intensity and density, that zoning had well preceded the redevelopment.
In many cases, the redevelopment was occurring prior to any publication of the plans to build Mopac.
And in fact, interestingly enough, since Mopac's been built up and been open, the conversion process has slowed down.
It was really a reflection of something that had already happened.
Now, because there was no access road built on Mopac, this limited any potential for strip development.
You know, it's really the way all urban freeways ought to be built.
I don't know if you've ever tried to get on Mopac, but if you don't know where the entry ramp is, you might drive all the way back to the river before you can get on.
I've done it once or twice.
It's kind of frustrating.
It's a planner, even.
Yes.
Well, you know, that happens.
Did it get lost in Austin?
Not very often.
So you wind up with an expressway that has limited access, that's infrequent, and it's hard to get on, and it has no service road.
And so it doesn't really have the level of community impact.
Now, it did separate some neighborhoods, and I won't deny that.
A lot of the area it went through was state land to begin with, reservations, National Guard posts, and so forth.
So Camp Mayberry.
And so, you know, a lot of things that happened.
Now, it did tend to stimulate some development on the north end at 183, where some of the interchanges are, but that would be expected.
Also, development was occurring in that direction in any case.
Mopac certainly reinforced that.
Now, when it comes to the south section of Mopac, something else entirely happened in the way it impacted South Austin.

because all of the methods of getting into North Austin from South Austin are terrible, suddenly the prospect of having a major underutilized freeway open, which could take you from South Austin, from a very desirable area to live in, in terms of scenery and terrain, very close into downtown, very close into the state bureaucratic headquarters, very close into the Capitol, and very close to the University of Texas,
on roads that essentially do not carry the traffic that they are capable of carrying, creates a tremendous potential for development in southwest Austin.
Furthermore, a certain nameless individual looks at this and sees an opportunity for building perhaps the largest shopping mall in Travis County.
You don't want to name him?
Well, we don't want to name everybody.
Well, he was a real estate agent who happened to be on the planning commission at the time and voted for the zoning change.
And then sold the land based on the contingency of the zoning change.
A little conflict of interest.
Shortly after that, there was an ethics thing passed by the city.
It sounds like the last high rise in La Jolla.
Yeah.
So...
moving right along past other little things.

But we see this tremendous shopping center with a tremendously large parking lot being built on top of an area that is going to drain into Barton Creek, which feeds into Barton Pool and Barton Springs, which is one of the very traditional ancient areas of Austin that the city holds in reverence.
It's a shrine, really, to the kind of character of the city.
Totally unpolluted spring water.
It doesn't have to be chlorinated.
People can go swimming in it.
It's rather chilly, but at the same time, you know, beautiful sloping area, grass covered, going down to a natural pool.
Well, here we have this tremendous shopping center with all the urban runoff, pollutants, oil, and everything else that's going to work its way down into there.
It spurs all kinds of residential development with the usual fertilizers, pesticides, herbicides,
leaking sewer pipes and whatnot, and people get very excited.
Furthermore, it's on top of the Edwards Aquifer recharge zone.

Well, the problem from the real estate agent's viewpoint, the developer's standpoint, is they had found out about all this, as they do when the plans are proposed and made public, and they go down and slowly begin to build up their land bank.
This is where they're going to build, beginning in the late 70s through the 80s.
Well, some of the developers said Barton Creek is going to be a real nightmare because it's so politically sacrosanct, so we'll go down to the next creek, Williamson Creek Watershed.
Again, Edwards Aquifer, same pollutant problems, runoff problems.
And this is where the commitment has been made by developers, the financial interest of the community, the bankers, that future development on large scale is going to occur.
Williamson.
Well, Williamson Creek and Barton Creek watershed, basically southwest Austin.
And the outcome, of course, of all of that is that now people are beginning to be a lot more environmentally aware.
Certainly in Austin, we have perhaps more civic organizations associated with environmental issues here per capita than any place else in the world that don't like this.
Well, here the investment's been made.
The speculation's been made.
There are financial commitments that have been made.
The land is generally, in many cases, either within the city limits, and you've got to allow them to do something or you've got to buy it.

And they figured out a few years ago that simply buying the Barton Creek floodplain, the creek itself and the adjacent land to it, not the entire drainage area, would run somewhere in the vicinity of $125 million.
Well, $125 million for the city of Austin is a massive development just to protect the bottom of the creek, when in fact you have to control the slopes and sides and the watershed to protect it.
Well, that's an economic infeasibility.
It just cannot be done.
Now, so here's the kind of massive problems that you're facing.
Others have spoken of the southwest corridor.
in a kind of a vague way on tape, and I haven't quite understood what they meant.
Well, the problem is you're moving into a recharge zone with some difficulties in terms of servicing.
It's going to be costly to service.
It's this hilly terrain.
And the outcome beyond that is that if you look around, there are a lot of areas in Austin that have problems of tremendous nature.
For example, the

East Austin area, east of the interstate, where most of the black, or I shouldn't say most, a large percentage of the black population resides, heavily black populated neighborhoods, is suffering terrible housing problems over there.
The deteriorated figures are running over 50%.
There is absolutely no economic investment, no incentive,
There was a bank established not too many years ago just right next to the interstate with the idea that it would service the area, be committed to it.
Well, it gave up this past year and moved to the other side of the interstate.
Symbolically, they could not remain in that community.
There is no investment in that area.
It's blighted.
It's deteriorating.
And it's got to the point that if I was
in a position to say something one way or the other, I would be saying, let's get the most vigorous code enforcement program we can in there and tear down every house and building we can.
And hopefully create a widely devastated area that's vacant so that we can hopefully rebuild.
Because it's to the point that it's almost that hopeless.
I'm not sure that we can do anything with that area.
From a professional standpoint, that would have to be my recommendation, regardless of the social impacts.
And my argument would be that people would be better off living elsewhere.
Now, that's always a hard thing to say when there's some sense of viable community there in some of that area.
So, you know, Austin has that as a problem.
They've got a transportation problem that's acute.
Their bus system is lousy.
It falls off every chart I've ever seen in terms of level of acceptable service or service frequencies.
You know, it's below poor.
You know, it just doesn't exist on the charts during the day time.
It's costly.
It has no method of permanent funding.
Every year they have to go in and battle taxes.
And so the outcome is that with everything going up associated with transportation, energy, oil, tires, it's a mess.
I don't see where the improvement is going to come from.
committee here in town is committed to light rail.
Well, light rail is wonderful.
I would love to have a choo-choo train, too, but the land patterns of Austin are in no way amenable to it.
The densities are wrong, and it gives you no flexibility whatsoever, and it's going to be extremely costly.
Are we running out of time?
And
And I don't mean to imply that people aren't aware of these problems.
For instance, they have initially lined up in the legislature this year
the possibility or prospect of creating a transit district.
This will be a bill that will be introduced during this legislative session, which allows the voters, by referendum, to establish a district.
And it creates the enabling legislation for every city in the state of Texas of over 300
they're not sure how it'll be written, but probably over 350,000 population, to initiate a referendum.
Well, this would be El Paso and Austin.
And anything above.
And anything above that wants to try again, like Dallas and Fort Worth, should they ever decide to try it again.
And from all the literature, certainly the only way to solve the problem would be through...
establishing a permanent trust fund through some taxing our transit district rather than having them to go and fight with the rest of the city for the budget.
The rapid growth has created some problems in terms of recreation also in parks in the city of Austin and that is the parks department is having a
I think, is a very effective department from what I've seen and what they're doing.
And I think they've got the priorities right.
But the outcome, of course, is that with the tremendously rapid growth, this creates tremendous demand and strain on their system, rapidly expanding system.
At the same time, people are saying, let's hold down prices.
Let's not increase taxes and so forth and so on.
Well, that's not what they need either.
So they've made the decision that essentially most of their money is going to be spent on purchasing of land and creating a land reserve for future development of parks.
They know if they don't get the land today or in the near future, they're not going to get it.
Well, you turn around, this means they're creating a rather large backlog of undeveloped parks.
And in fact,
We have at least one nice little linear park in South Austin that's supposed to tie into Town Lake that has never been developed.
It's been on the city tax rolls or city park rolls now since the 40s, undeveloped.

And this happens to run through a predominantly Mexican-American section of town, and this has become a focal point for an active community association to begin to focus some attention and some grievances on some problems that the city has managed to ignore.
It's a typical thing.
The squeaky wheel is going to get attention and create some improvements.
So you begin with the problem of
saying, well, we've got to do this for the long term.
But on the other hand, we've got to solve some of these short range problems.
And there's not money for both.
And it creates a very complex situation.
Austin is fortunate in that generally, the citizens have been willing to support bond issues at a level that I find very difficult to believe after I've worked and seen other communities operate.
We did have a major bond proposal shot down, package shot down.
as it was last year.
But it was mainly tended to be a response to some growth issues and some concern over the direction of growth and where it was going to be located.

Interestingly enough, things that the voters perceived as being needed and that did not have negative growth connotations, environmental impacts associated with them, like the parks package, the police package, the EMS package, the fire department package, were all funded.

On things that failed were things like the sewer development plant, which included a major interceptor line running into a recharge area, a water line that would open up one of these sensitive areas for development that was part of a larger package.
Well, the city is committed to developing those areas.
People own the land.
They have the right to develop.

And with the wonderful municipal utility district laws of the state of Texas, if the city refuses to hook people up, ultimately they're going to be able to establish their own municipal utility district and build anyway.
The problem is that the city of Austin really is not in a good position to say no.
It cannot say no under the state law of Texas.
It can slow you down and make your life miserable, but it cannot stop growth from occurring.
It can make it more attractive in some other areas.
Dick Lowy commented in much the same way on this point.
And of course, it must be a source of tremendous frustration
Oh, it is.

The city is essentially left with the prospect of saying, well, we're either going to leave you on your own as a rural and incorporated subdivision with the prospect that you may at some time be brought into the city with an inadequate infrastructure and inadequate utility system,
or else you're going to incorporate and form your own community within the geographic region and base of the city.
One commitment the city of Austin has is not to allow that to happen.

They look at Dallas, they look at even more substantially cities in the Northeast, and there is a commitment that the city of Austin, as it is growing, will maintain control over what it perceives to be its political and economic region.
It will not allow a series of fractionalized rural communities and villages to grow up
which will derive most of the sustenance from the city as a whole while not paying a reasonable share for the support of that city.
And I don't think anybody politically in the city of Austin is going to take any other position.

To a certain extent, certain neighborhoods and communities are beginning to have some qualms because they don't feel they're getting quite the level of service and attention as quickly as they should get.
when there's a lot of money being pumped into these rural and outlying areas.
But we've almost got ourselves in Austin to the point that we can't get off the horse.
Because we have got ourselves committed in terms of funding programs, in terms of utilities.
And for instance, we own our city electric system, which is a source of probably considerable comment.
The county owns the hospital.
And the county owns, well, we own the hospital.
Oh, the city does.
The city owns the hospital.
That's a continuing source of political debate.
Yeah.
And essentially, we...
are like New York, have our own welfare system in the city of Austin, and like everybody else in the world, because we own our hospital.
And we supply to residents free medical care as necessary, which I don't argue with personally, but it's costly.
It adds up.
Well, in the case of the electric department, we are so overcommitted
in terms of generation capacity.
Particularly if new facilities come online, if we ever get South Texas Nuclear Project open and running ever, we will be so over committed in terms of generation capacity that if we don't grow,
the cost of electricity is going to go up at over twice the rate of which we currently project the cost to go up.
In other words, we're looking at, say, a continuing increase of about 6% a year, if I remember my numbers right.
If we don't grow at a certain percentage rate that's been geared into this projection, we will trip up to about 10% a year increase, which gets pretty substantial.
It's already high.
And it's a very high rate as it is.
So by continuing to grow, we're holding
the ultimate cost of our electricity down.
But if we don't grow, that means all of us that are here are going to have to pay more money in the future.
And I don't know what the outcome of that is going to be, but it certainly seems...
I think Lily mentioned selling, but Austin's currently selling electricity in Houston.
Oh yes, we are.
And we increased the cell contract to Houston.
Houston is, in fact, paying us $18 million a year just for the right to buy electricity from us.
That doesn't include the purchase of the electricity.
That's just the right million and a half dollars a month just to be able to buy electricity, if they need it.
And then they will pay premium price, maximum price, for the electricity we generate.
And we'll sell the cheaper electricity we generate from our coal plant and the nuclear plant, ultimately, to the citizens.
Well, this is one way to hold down that 6%.
That pared it back down.

you know again you know I'm not sure that that's necessarily a good way to go about making money um you know you certainly don't want to be in a position of not being able to have power and I certainly think that this is some of the decisions that we've made in regard to electrical energy are probably better ones because you know if you ever get behind and have to buy it you can uh you can be in the position of Houston paying somebody for the right to maybe buy it someday and Con Ed
And New York faced that problem of having to buy electricity over a long period of time in large quantities.
And the outcome was the system essentially went to a point of being bankrupt and having the highest electric rates in the US.
Your former home state of Utah was entirely blacked out yesterday.
Which is another good reason to show that we ought to be putting money into maintenance.
And the point that a lot of people don't include is, what is the cost of that blackout in terms of lost work time, lost sales, equipment damage, accidents?
And if you look at the social cost and consequences, just to the disruption of business, the cost is tremendous.
They couldn't pump gas for police cars.
Our ambulances are fire trucks, and your pumps go off for your water system, and suddenly you don't have water to fight fires.
It goes on and on.
So certainly that is something that we have to try.
We have to have it, and we don't know what the answer to that issue is.
In terms of opportunities...
You know, Austin's growing.
It's got a healthy economy.
It's vigorous.
We've got a tremendously educated and versatile population.
Site-wise, it's well located climatically.
It's not really that humid.
And on the other hand, we're not quite as hot as Dallas in the summertime, and we're not quite as cold as them in the winter.
Not quite as humid as College Station.
Yeah.
a little bit more pleasant all the way around.
There's a lot of activities.

State capitals are kind of a funny beast, per se, because they always seem to have a good stable economy because there's a large state bureaucracy located there that's, if not paid well, at least paid adequately.
And you frequently see a major university there.
We have the University of Texas here
you know, some 44,000, 45,000 students that are willing to work cheap and also a well-educated faculty and talented researchers.

This brings a lot of culture and diversity into the community that a community this size would not otherwise have or would probably be paying through the nose in order to try to maintain a semblance of it.
We have a lot of
theaters, very good cultural facilities, good restaurants, a diverse population and ethnically, which I think adds to a community.
So I'm not too concerned about the future of Austin as I might be about a lot of other communities.
Well, I've heard it said by some people outside of Austin who know Austin rather well and may have lived here, in fact, in the past.
that they feel that Austin should have stopped four years ago.
Oh, well, yeah, everybody says that.
They do.
All right.
Well, now, why do people say that?
And why do they feel that what's being done now is contrary to the best interests of Austin?
Oh, I think there's a lot of romanticism attached with when we were young.
I think that people remember Austin from the time they went to the University of Texas here and what a good time it was.
Indeed.
And I think a lot of us look back at our undergraduate days and say, maybe that was the best time of my life.
In many ways, I was young, healthy, and I really didn't realize all of the limitations I really have.
Did you go to UT, also?
No.
I was wondering.
No.
But I appreciated the social life at Texas.
Matter of fact, my junior year, I spent as much time over here as possible.
I left Aggieland on weekends.
There wasn't much to do that attracted me there.
Difficult.
Yes.
But the outcome, of course, is that we remember the way things were and were attracted to it.

In a lot of ways, Austin in the 50s and maybe the 60s probably was kind of the optimum as a community because if you're looking at a population, say, somewhere between 50,000, which it was in the 40s,
running up to maybe 150,000 to 200,000, you really don't have some of the complex social problems that you have with a larger community.
The taxes are generally quite moderate and low because you don't have the level and cross-section of demand of social structures and problems.
The community wasn't growing.
Its infrastructure was largely paid for.
Its park system was developed and operating and adequate to its population.
So we can look back at it and say, hey, that was a good balance.
It had museums.
It had reached perhaps the minimum level of critical mass to support an incredible variety of community services.
Yes, and an incredible variety of recreational activities and restaurants.
But at the same time, it hadn't got to the point that suddenly we really had to begin to pay for a lot of the additional costs that occur with growth.
And the cedar is coming out.
No, the cat.
The cat.
Oh.
So the outcome, of course, is that a lot of us would look back and say, oh, wasn't that wonderful?
That's what we really want.
And we look back and say, gee, I could have managed to buy a house very reasonably, a very nice house.
Today, you know, I can barely afford to pay my electric bill.
Taxes are high.
And so, and it's harder to get around.
You know, today you cannot really drive around Austin that easily.
Okay, so I think a lot of people will look back and they will pick some time in the past and say Austin should have stopped there.
Now, some of the old timers should have said it's been like, you know, it's gone downhill since the GIs got back during World War II.
World War II was the best time ever.
All the students were gone, and it was decent for a change.
You could drive through the University of Texas and get a parking place on campus.
Incredible.
Yeah, impossible.
Probably the 50s and 60s, in many ways, were kind of a peak period for the city of Austin.
There was a lot of self-confidence, and we weren't that sensitive to some of the problems that existed.
It was no big deal that certain parts of Boston had flooding problems and that certain people didn't live very well or had very inadequate houses, or their incomes were extremely low.
So I think a lot of the sensitivity that we're aware of in terms of our problems today, we just didn't have back then.
But if we really look back at it,
And for some people, it really wasn't that good a period.
So there's a lot of trade-offs in every community.
And I think that Austin is facing those today.
In a way that they've never had in the past.
In a way that they've never had to do in the past.
This creates a lot of concern.
There's a lot of people that feel like they're losing status and position.
There's a much greater turmoil and changeover.
You've got major industries coming into town that are beginning to employ people for, if not decent wages, at least certainly adequate wages.
TI, Westinghouse, Motorola, IBM.
or major employers in town.
And they, although don't pay at the scale they do in St. California, they are certainly paying above what has been the tradition in the service industries associated with Austin.
So, you know, you begin to see people having opportunities in Austin.
It's not a matter of if you lose your job with the city or Texas University or the state bureaucracy that you're suddenly forced to necessarily leave town.
Mm-hmm.

There are many departments at Texas that are just frantic because they can't keep the people employed because the people were committed to living in Austin, but suddenly they find they can make what they're worth by going across the street to IBM.
And this just distresses people that we can't maintain things the way they were.
I think having more opportunities in many ways is better for Austin and its residents than, say, it was during the 50s and 60s.
I would have taken a real financial beating to try to live here in the 50s or 60s, I think, as compared to today.
Not that I'm doing that well today.
Well, who is at the university level?
Yes.
Kevin, thank you very much for your views on Austin.
It will make a real contribution to the book, I'm sure.
If anything else comes up, keep in touch, and we'll add it to the transcriptions.
Appreciate it.
Thank you.
